Here is the primary issue hiding in your telemetry buffer code:

## The Diagnosis

The bug is the classic Python trap of using a **mutable default argument** (`frame_buffer: list = []`) in your `__init__` method.

In Python, default arguments are evaluated only once when the function or class is first defined, not every time you instantiate a new object. This means **every single instance** of `TelemetryBuffer` that you create without explicitly passing a `frame_buffer` list will share the exact same list in memory.

If `Channel_A` pushes a frame, it will accidentally show up in the buffer for `Channel_B`. This shared state will cause premature `MemoryError` buffer overflows across your channels because they are all piling data into the same underlying list.

