```

The parent class `AvionicsPeripheral` defines a strict contract: `poll_raw_voltage` must return a **floating-point voltage** ($0.0\text{V}$ to $5.0\text{V}$). While `LiDARPeripheral` and `GPSPeripheral` adhere to this contract, `IMUPeripheral` breaks it when a high drift factor triggers an internal calibration fault. Instead of returning a float, it returns a dictionary (`error_packet`).

Additionally, look at line 52:

```python
self.buffer.push_frame(time.time(), 0.0)

```

Your `TelemetryBuffer.push_frame` method (from our previous fix) explicitly expects a **float** for its `voltage_level` argument. While passing `0.0` here works technically, returning a dictionary object to the main bus architecture will cause a crash (like an `AttributeError` or `TypeError`) down the line when the system attempts to process or log the returned data as a numerical voltage reading.



The Lesson

When overriding methods in child classes, always respect the signature contracts (return types and expected arguments) established by the parent class. Breaking a return type contract breaks polymorphism and forces the rest of your system to include messy type checking logic.

